solution.p:
Equivalently, we are asking if the homogeneous vector equation
x\vec{1 1 1} + y\vec{1 -1 2} + z\vec{3 1 4} = \vec{0 0 0}
has a nontrivial solution.  We solve this by forming a matrix and row reducing (we do not augment because of this ):
\mat{1 1 3; 1 -1 1; 1 2 4}
\quad\xrightarrow{\text{row reduce}}\quad
\mat{1 0 2; 0 1 1; 0 0 0}
This says x = -2z and y = -z.  So there exist nontrivial solutions: for instance, taking z=1 gives this equation of linear dependence:
-2\vec{1 1 1} - \vec{1 -1 2} + \vec{3 1 4} = \vec{0 0 0}.

Equivalently, we are asking if the homogeneous vector equation
x\vec{1 1 -2} + y\vec{1 -1 2} + z\vec{3 1 4} = \vec{0 0 0}
has a nontrivial solution.  We solve this by forming a matrix and row reducing (we do not augment because of this ):
\mat{1 1 3; 1 -1 1; -2 2 4}
\quad\xrightarrow{\text{row reduce}}\quad
\mat{1 0 0; 0 1 0; 0 0 1}
This says x = y = z = 0, i.e., the only solution is the trivial solution.  We conclude that the set is linearly independent.

subsection.p:
A set containg one vector \{v\} is linearly independent when v\neq 0, since xv = 0 implies x=0.


